  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the advantages of mean, median, and mode?",
  "response": "The **mean**, **median**, and **mode** are measures of central tendency, each with its own advantages depending on the nature of the data and the purpose of analysis. Here's a breakdown of the advantages of each:\n\n### 1. **Mean (Arithmetic Average)**\n   - **Sensitive to all data points**: The mean takes into account every value in the dataset, making it representative of the entire dataset.\n   - **Useful for further calculations**: It is often used in statistical formulas, such as variance and standard deviation.\n   - **Computationally simple**: Easy to calculate and understand.\n   - **Works well with symmetric distributions**: For normally distributed data, the mean provides a good measure of central tendency.\n   - **Summation property**: The sum of deviations from the mean is zero, which is useful in statistical analysis.\n\n   **Best for**: Continuous data with a normal distribution or when all values are equally important.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Median (Middle Value)**\n   - **Resistant to outliers**: The median is not affected by extreme values or skewed distributions, making it a robust measure of central tendency.\n   - **Represents the middle of the data**: Useful for understanding the \"typical\" value in a dataset, especially for ordinal or skewed data.\n   - **Works well with skewed distributions**: More appropriate than the mean for data with extreme values or non-symmetric distributions.\n   - **Easy to interpret**: Simply the middle value of the dataset when ordered.\n\n   **Best for**: Skewed distributions, ordinal data, or datasets with outliers.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Mode (Most Frequent Value)**\n   - **Represents the most common value**: Useful for identifying the most frequent or popular value in a dataset.\n   - **Works with categorical data**: The only measure of central tendency that can be used for nominal data (e.g., colors, categories).\n   - **Simple to identify**: In some cases, the mode can be easily spotted without calculations.\n   - **Can be used for multimodal distributions**: A dataset can have multiple modes, which is useful for identifying multiple peaks in the data distribution.\n\n   **Best for**: Categorical data, discrete data, or datasets with a clear peak in frequency.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Advantages:\n- **Mean**: Best for normal distributions and continuous data, sensitive to all values.\n- **Median**: Best for skewed distributions or data with outliers, robust and resistant to extremes.\n- **Mode**: Best for categorical data or identifying the most frequent value.\n\nChoosing the appropriate measure depends on the data type, distribution, and the specific context of the analysis.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
